Treating the same disease with different methods reflects the flexibility of treatment based on syndrome differentiation.
Treating different diseases with the same therapy applies when different diseases manifest the same syndrome.
When measles eruption is delayed at the early stage, the eruption-promoting method should be applied.
In the middle stage of measles dominated by lung heat, lung heat should be cleared.
Yin-Yang theory can be used to analyze physiological activities of the human body.
Yin-Yang theory can be used to explain pathological changes of disease.
Motion pertains to Yang, and stillness pertains to Yin.
The exterior pertains to Yang, and the interior pertains to Yin.
The upper pertains to Yang, and the lower pertains to Yin.
Heat pertains to Yang, and cold pertains to Yin.
Function pertains to Yang, and substance pertains to Yin.
The back of the human body mostly pertains to Yang, while the abdomen mostly pertains to Yin.
The lateral sides of the limbs mostly pertain to Yang, while the medial sides mostly pertain to Yin.
Loss of balance between Yin and Yang can lead to disease.
Excess of Yang produces heat, while excess of Yin produces cold.
Yang deficiency produces cold, while Yin deficiency produces heat.
Wood has the properties of growth and free unfolding.
Fire has the properties of warmth and upward flaring.
Earth has the properties of generation, transformation and reception.
Metal has the properties of purification, descending and astringing.
Water has the properties of moistening and flowing downward.
Disease of the mother organ can affect the child organ.
Disease of the child organ can also affect the mother organ.
Reinforcing the mother is used to treat deficiency syndrome of the child organ.
Reducing the child is used to treat excess syndrome of the mother organ.
Nourishing water to moisten wood nourishes liver Yin by enriching kidney Yin.
Benefiting fire to reinforce earth assists spleen Yang by warming kidney Yang.
Mutual promotion of metal and water nourishes the lungs and kidneys simultaneously.
Building up earth to generate metal replenishes lung Qi by strengthening the spleen and Qi.
Inhibiting wood to support earth harmonizes the liver and spleen by soothing the liver and strengthening the spleen.
Assisting metal to subdue wood restrains liver wood by purifying lung Qi.
Draining the south and tonifying the north nourishes kidney water by purging heart fire.
The heart governs blood and vessels by relying on heart Qi to propel blood circulation.
Malnutrition of the mind can lead to abnormal mental activities.
The lungs are delicate organs and are easily invaded by exogenous pathogens.
The dispersing function of lung Qi can distribute defensive Qi to the body surface.
The descending function of lung Qi can keep the respiratory tract clear.
The spleen governs transformation of fluids to prevent dampness accumulation.
Spleen Qi ascending the clear can distribute essence upward.
Failure of the spleen to control blood can cause chronic bleeding.
When liver free coursing is normal, Qi movement remains smooth.
Dysfunction of the liver in storing blood can affect menstruation.
Insufficiency of liver blood can deprive tendons and vessels of nourishment.
When kidney essence is sufficient, the sea of marrow is nourished.
Insecurity of kidney Qi can lead to failure to restrain urination and defecation.
Improper feeding in children easily impairs the spleen and stomach.
Poor regulation of cold and warmth in children makes them susceptible to exogenous pathogens.
At the onset of sores and ulcers, the strength of pathogenic toxins should be differentiated.
Surgical syndrome differentiation should combine local symptoms with systemic manifestations.
After pus and slough are removed, granulation growth and wound closure should be promoted.
Viscera manifestations reflect the functions of internal organs on the body surface.
Dysfunction of Zang-Fu organs can appear through external manifestations.
The five Zang-organs mainly function to store vital essence.
The six Fu-organs mainly function to transport and transform food and drink.
Normal functions of the five Zang-organs allow vital essence to be abundant.
Normal descending and free passage of the six Fu-organs enables smooth transformation of food and drink.
Heart Yang warms the blood vessels to maintain blood circulation.
When heart blood is sufficient, the mind is nourished.
The dispersing function of the lungs distributes body fluids to the body surface.
The descending function of the lungs sends fluids downward to the kidneys.
Spleen-Qi ascending the clear helps maintain the position of internal organs.
Failure of the spleen to ascend the clear can cause sinking of middle Qi.
Normal free coursing of Liver-Qi keeps emotions smooth.
Stagnation of Liver-Qi can affect the ascent and descent of the spleen and stomach.
Kidney essence transforms into marrow to nourish brain marrow.
The storing function of kidney-Qi helps control urination and defecation.
Smooth gallbladder Qi helps the excretion of bile.
Harmonious descent of stomach-Qi helps food and drink move downward.
Dysfunction of large-intestine transportation can cause constipation or diarrhea.
Dysfunction of urinary-bladder Qi transformation can cause difficult urination.
Meridian disorders can reflect abnormalities of related Zang-Fu organs.
Unsmooth channel-Qi can cause pain and numbness.
Meridian obstruction can restrict the movement of Qi and blood.
The circulation of the twelve regular channels connects the interior and exterior, upper and lower.
The eight extraordinary vessels regulate Qi and blood in the regular channels.
Insufficiency of Yang-Qi in the Governor Vessel can affect all Yang channels of the body.
Disharmony of the Conception Vessel can affect uterine and fetal functions.
Disharmony of the Thoroughfare Vessel can affect the movement of Qi and blood.
Changes in tongue color help identify cold, heat, deficiency and excess.
The thickness of tongue coating helps judge the strength of pathogens and healthy Qi.
Moistness or dryness of tongue coating can reflect the state of body fluids.
Floating or deep pulse position helps distinguish exterior from interior.
Slow or rapid pulse rate helps distinguish cold from heat.
The strength of the pulse helps judge the relative strength of healthy Qi and pathogens.
Examination of infantile finger veins can help judge the depth of disease.
Superficial infantile finger veins often indicate disease in the exterior.
Deep and stagnant infantile finger veins often indicate disease in the interior.
