Yang-type sores and ulcers are often caused by exuberant fire toxin.
Clear consciousness often indicates that the mind is nourished.
Clouded consciousness often indicates phlegm-fire disturbing the heart.
A sallow complexion is often related to spleen deficiency with insufficiency of Qi and blood.
A dark complexion often indicates internal obstruction by blood stasis.
A pale and puffy complexion is often related to insufficiency of Yang-Qi.
An enlarged tongue body often indicates internal retention of water-dampness.
A thin tongue body often indicates insufficiency of Yin and blood.
Tooth marks on the tongue often indicate spleen deficiency with exuberant dampness.
A dark-purple tongue body often indicates obstruction by blood stasis.
A greasy coating often indicates internal retention of damp turbidity or phlegm-fluid.
Scanty coating often indicates insufficiency of stomach Yin.
Peeled coating often indicates damage to stomach Qi and stomach Yin.
Thirst with preference for cold drinks often indicates exuberant interior heat.
Bland taste without thirst often indicates cold-dampness encumbering the spleen.
Bitter taste is often related to dampness-heat in the liver and gallbladder.
Poor appetite is often related to failure of the spleen to transport properly.
